          "id": "col-l04-c1",
          "title": "The Rise and Fall of the SSC",
          "content": "In this lesson, we explore the captivating history of the Superconducting Super Collider (SSC), a groundbreaking project that was intended to be built in Waxahachie, Texas. The SSC was conceived during the 1980s, a time when the United States was heavily investing in scientific advancements under the leadership of President Reagan. This ambitious project aimed to create the world's most powerful particle accelerator, designed as an enormous 54-mile (87-kilometer) circular tunnel. Its purpose was to collide protons at an astonishing energy level of 40 trillion electron volts, which would have far surpassed the capabilities of any existing particle accelerator at that time.\nThe SSC was not just a machine; it represented the pinnacle of American high-energy physics research. Scientists believed that it would lead to groundbreaking discoveries, including the elusive Higgs boson, various supersymmetric particles, and even new physics concepts that could extend beyond the established Standard Model of particle physics. In 1987, Congress recognized the potential of this project and approved funding, with an initial estimated cost of $4.4 billion.\nHowever, as the project progressed, unexpected challenges began to arise. The geological conditions at the Texas site proved to be more complicated than anticipated, leading to significant delays and increased costs. Additionally, the management of such a large-scale scientific endeavor presented its own set of difficulties. Engineering at the forefront of science is always a complex task, and the SSC was no exception. By 1993, the estimated cost of the project had ballooned to nearly three times the original budget, raising concerns among lawmakers.\nFaced with growing budget pressures and a rising skepticism about the value of large scientific projects, Congress ultimately made the difficult decision to cancel the SSC. At that time, an impressive 14 miles of tunnel had already been excavated, and approximately $2 billion had been invested in the project. The cancellation of the SSC was a pivotal moment in the field of particle physics, as it marked a significant shift in focus from the United States to Europe, where other large-scale projects, such as the Large Hadron Collider (LHC), began to take precedence. This lesson not only highlights the ambitious vision behind the SSC but also serves as a reminder of the challenges and complexities involved in scientific research and funding.\nContext recap: In this lesson, we explore the captivating history of the Superconducting Super Collider (SSC), a groundbreaking project that was intended to be built in Waxahachie, Texas. The SSC was conceived during the 1980s, a time when the United States was heavily investing in scientific advancements under the leadership of President Reagan. This ambitious project aimed to create the world's most powerful particle accelerator, designed as an enormous 54-mile (87-kilometer) circular tunnel. Its purpose was to collide protons at an astonishing energy level of 40 trillion electron volts, which would have far surpassed the capabilities of any existing particle accelerator at that time.\nWhy this matters: The Rise and Fall of the SSC helps learners in Science connect ideas from Collider: The Search for the World's Smallest Particles to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
